<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900507-0030</DOCNO><DOCID>900507-0030.</DOCID><HL>   Senate Panel to Study   Firm's Possible Conflict   In U.S.-Japan Accord</HL><DATE>05/07/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C10</SO><CO>   JAPAN</CO><IN>MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)NUCLEAR POWER, FUEL (NUK)</IN><GV>CONGRESS (CNG)ENERGY DEPARTMENT (ERG)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The Senate Governmental Affairs Committeewill investigate a potential conflict-of-interest involving aWashington consulting firm that simultaneously servedJapanese utilities and advised the Energy Department on aU.S.-Japan energy agreement.   &quot;We are now learning that foreign and domestic commercialinterests may have had a hand not only in negotiating theagreement, but in selling it on Capitol Hill,&quot; said Sen. JohnGlenn (D., Ohio), chairman of the panel. He cited a recentarticle in The Wall Street Journal.</LP><TEXT>   The agreement lessened U.S. controls over future shipmentsof plutonium to Japan, material derived from U.S. nuclearfuel. The company, International Energy Associates Ltd., hasadmitted that while advising the U.S. on the accord, itprovided newsletters to the Japanese utilities describing theinternal administration fight over the agreement. Thenewsletters also discussed &quot;anti-plutonium hard-liners,&quot;including Sen. Glenn, who were opposed to the pact.   The firm, which has since changed its name toEnvironmental andamp; Energy Services Co., insists that it fullydisclosed the newsletter and its contract with the Japaneseutilities to the Energy Department, as it was required to doby federal law. Energy Department officials say they weresurprised to learn about the newsletters.</TEXT></DOC>